# Supabase Guidelines

## Authentication

- We are using SSR for authentication, NOT auth helpers
- Use server-side authentication flows with cookies
- Implement proper CSRF protection
- Handle auth state changes appropriately
- Use appropriate role-based access control (RBAC)

## Database

- Use Supabase migrations for schema changes
- Follow naming conventions for tables and columns:
  - Use snake_case for table and column names
  - Use plural for table names (e.g., `users`, `products`)
  - Use singular for junction tables (e.g., `user_product`)
- Add appropriate indexes for frequently queried columns
- Set up proper foreign key constraints
- Use RLS (Row Level Security) policies for data access control

## API Calls

- Use typed queries with the generated types
- Implement proper error handling for all database operations
- Use transactions for operations that modify multiple tables
- Avoid N+1 query problems by using appropriate joins
- Cache frequently accessed data when appropriate

## Real-time

- Use Supabase real-time features for live updates
- Implement proper channel and event handling
- Consider performance implications of real-time subscriptions
- Unsubscribe from channels when components unmount

## Storage

- Organize files in appropriate buckets
- Set up proper access control for storage buckets
- Handle file uploads with proper validation
- Implement appropriate file size limits

## Type Generation

- Keep types up to date by running:
  ```
  npx supabase gen types typescript --project-id xbwfjonmiddqfrgwdhmi > src/types/supabase.ts
  ```
- Use the generated types for all Supabase operations
- Extend types as needed for specific use cases

## Edge Functions

- Use Edge Functions for server-side logic that needs to be close to users
- Keep Edge Functions small and focused
- Implement proper error handling in Edge Functions
- Test Edge Functions thoroughly before deployment